1.3 The hypothesies to test:

  • Education plays a role in voter turnout because the more educated one is the more likely one will be politically informed and involved.
  • Corruption effects voter turnout because the more corrupt a country is the less likely the election will be legitimate resulting in less voter turnout
  • years.democ: Due to the the longevity of democracy the value that people place on it has depreciated which weakens voter turnout.

2 Effect of education on turnout

A country with a population who has higher education will result in a higher voter turnout

Column name is educ

2.1 Univariate analysis

Line represents where Canada is

ggplot(Turnout, aes(educ)) +
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 11.617)
## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

2.2 Bivariate analysis

ggplot(Turnout, aes(educ, turnout)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 27 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Observation: seems like theres a relationship

2.2.1 Statistical test - R correlation

  • Null hypothesis: true correlation is equal to 0
  • Alternate hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
cor.test(Turnout$educ, Turnout$turnout, use = "complete")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Turnout$educ and Turnout$turnout
## t = 2.6152, df = 47, p-value = 0.01195
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.08359762 0.57953020
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3564158

Correlation value is 0.3564158 which is a weakly positive relationship, and the p-value of this correlation is 0.01195, so we are at least 95% confident that this correlation value is real

2.3 Conclusion

Looks like more education leads to higher voter turnout, but Canada is already doing well on that so nothing to recommend.

## Warning: Removed 7 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).

Observation: looks like a really shitty correlation

3.2.1 Statistical test - R correlation

  • Null hypothesis: true correlation is equal to 0
  • Alternate hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
cor.test(Turnout$corrupt, Turnout$turnout, use = "complete")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Turnout$corrupt and Turnout$turnout
## t = 2.7572, df = 67, p-value = 0.007505
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.08928646 0.51685197
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3192213

Correlation value is 0.3192213 which is weak positive relationship, and the p-value of this correlation is 0.007505, so can reject the null hypothesis that the true correlation is 0 and be confident that there is an actual correlation

3.3 Conclusion

corrupt: A continuous measure of the perceived level of political corruption in the country. Higher values mean lower perceived corruption.

Less corrupt countries (higher value) tend to have higher voter turnout. Canadas corrpution score is 9, so Canada is already doing pretty well here and probably cant improve.

4.3 Conclusion

Countries with longer years of democracy tend to have higher voter turnout. Canada has one of the highest years of democracy already do nothing for Canada to do here.

model = lm(turnout ~ elec.year + elec.type + compulsory + competitiveness + democ.type + bicameral + DM + ENPP + years.democ + corrupt + educ + pop, turnout_complete)

5.1 Checking compulsory

(because otherwise you dont have any t-tests or ANOVA tests)

The column name is compulsory

5.1.1 Univariate analysis

Using a bar chart

ggplot(Turnout, aes(compulsory)) +
  geom_bar()

5.1.2 Bivariate analysis

5.1.2.1 Plot

Using boxplot

ggplot(Turnout, aes(compulsory, turnout)) +
  geom_boxplot()

5.1.2.2 Statistical test - ANOVA

  • Null: there is no relationship between turnout and compulsory
  • Alternate: there is a relationship between turnout and compulsory
anova(lm(turnout ~ compulsory, Turnout))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: turnout
##            Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value    Pr(>F)    
## compulsory  2  3646.9  1823.5  9.2234 0.0002683 ***
## Residuals  73 14432.2   197.7                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Pvalue is 0.0002683, which is below the 0.05 threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and lend support for the alternative hypothesis: there is a relationship between compulsory and turnout

5.1.2.3 Statistical test - T-test

The difference here is that we are directly comparing two groups, whereas before we were comparing all groups

  • Null: countries with Enforced have same turnout as countries that are Not enforced
  • Alternate: countries with Not Enforced have different turnout commpared to countries that are Not enforced
turnout_notenforced = subset(Turnout, compulsory != "No")
t.test(turnout ~ compulsory, turnout_notenforced)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  turnout by compulsory
## t = 4.6318, df = 6.8836, p-value = 0.0025
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  11.68233 36.22338
## sample estimates:
##     mean in group Enforced mean in group Not Enforced 
##                   88.88000                   64.92714

Pvalue is 0.0025, which is below the 0.05 threshold. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and we can conclude that enforcing compulsory voting leads to higher voter turnout.

5.1.3 Conclusion

Countries should have compulsory voting to increase voter turnout. Also, countries with compulsory voting should enforce it to have a higher increase in voter turnout compared to unenforced. Canada does not have compulsory voting, so one might recommend that Canada makes voting compulsory and enforce it
